s -- t20. Descartes: “All Things Which I Conceive Clearly and Distinctly in Corporeal Objects Are in Them” -- t21. Why Was Descartes a Foundationalist? -- t22. Cartesian Passions and the Union of Mind and Body -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in this volume form a commentary on Descartes' Meditations. Following the sequence of the meditational stages, the authors analyze the function of each stage in transforming the reader, to realize his essential nature as a rational inquirer, capable of scientific, demonstrable knowledge of the world. There are essays on the genre of meditational writing, on the implications of the opening cathartic section of the book on Descartes' theory of perception and his use of skeptical arguments; essays on the theory of ideas and their role of Descartes' reconstructive analytic method; essays on the proofs for the existence of God, on the role of the will in the formation and malformation of judgments; and the essays on the foundations of the science of extension and on Descartes' account of the union of mind and body.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFirst philosophy. 0aMetaphysics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  acartesian philosophy.  acollection of essays.  acontemporary philosophers.  acritical analysis.  acritical commentary.  adescartes.  aexistence of god.  afree will.  aknowledge.  ameditational writing.  ameditations.  amind and body.  amodern philosophy.  anonfiction.  aphilosophical.  arational thought.  areconstructive analysis.  ascience of extension.  ascientific knowledge.  askeptical arguments.  astages of meditations.  atheory of ideas.  atheory of perception.  awestern philosophy.1 aBaier, Anne